    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Work or Family? Both.</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Sherry F Colb letter on Cameron Stracher's Sept 2 article hails employers who provide child care at office for expanding options of working families</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Child Care and Other Traps,'' by Cameron Stracher (Op-Ed, Sept. 2):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Child Care and Other Traps,'' by Cameron Stracher (Op-Ed, Sept. 2):</p>
        <p>Mr. Stracher says employers who provide child care at the office harm families by enabling them to ''avoid the hard choices we should be making. Work or family? Home or office? We can't have it all.''</p>
        <p>He presents a false choice. Going to the office can add a richness to the lives of many parents that they would miss if they stayed at home. There are some very loving parents who would hate to be away from their babies from early in the morning until late at night, but would find monotonous and even depressing the prospect of spending all day, every day, caring for an infant.</p>
        <p>Though ''having it all'' remains an elusive goal, we should applaud the efforts of employers who expand the options of working families so that no one is forced to choose between working and being a parent.</p>
        <p>SHERRY F. COLB  Newark, Sept. 2, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a law professor at Rutgers University.</p>
      </block>
